LABEL
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------
it adds metadata to the image, description, who is the owner, which project. Labels are used to filter the images.
create a folder name as LABEL in VS code, under LABEL create file Dockerfile. add a content as below
FROM almalinux:9
LABEL authoru="deepika" \
      Company="HCL" \
      topic="docker file" \
      duration="2 hours"

go to git bash ==> git add . , git commit -m "docker", git push main origin
now the changes reflected in git hub and run git pull in putty it updates the changes.
cd dockerfiles/LABEL
]docker build -t label:v1 .
]docker images -f 'label=company=HCL'   -> it searches in 100's of images of HCL and it shows HCL.
] docker inspect <image id>  => it shows the all details

EXPOSE
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
used to let the users to know what are the ports this container opens when it runs.. Expose instruction will not effect functionality it will only gives info.
create a folder name as EXPOSE in VS code, under EXPOSE create file Dockerfile. add a content as below
FROM almalinux:9
RUN dnfinstall nginx -y
EXPOSE 80
CMD ["nginx", "-g" "daemon off;"]

go to git bash ==> git add . , git commit -m "docker", git push main origin
now the changes reflected in git hub and run git pull in putty it updates the changes.

cd dockerfiles/EXPOSE
docker build -t expose:v1
docker images
docker inspect <image-ID of expose> -> it shows the exposed port details.

ENV
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
ENV is useful to set any API URLS or any URLS.
sets the environment variables, these can be used inside container.
create a folder name as ENV in VS code, under ENV create file Dockerfile. add a content as below
FROM almalinux:9
ENV course="Devops with AWS" \
    trainer="viswanath" \
    duration="120hrs" \

go to git bash ==> git add . , git commit -m "docker", git push main origin
now the changes reflected in git hub and run git pull in putty it updates the changes.
cd dockerfiles/ENV
docker run -d env:v1 sleep 100
docker exec -it cntainerid bash
you can login to bash 
type env
here you can see all the varaibales all these variables developers can use in coding

COPY
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
used files to copy from local to images.
create a folder name as COPY in VS code, under COPY create file Dockerfile. add a content as below
FROM almalinux:9
RUN dnf install nginx -y
RUN rm -rf /usr/share/nginx/html/index.html
COPY index.html /usr/share/nginx/html/index.html
CMD ["nginx", "-g" "daemon off;"]

go to git bash ==> git add . , git commit -m "docker", git push main origin
now the changes reflected in git hub and run git pull in putty it updates the changes.
cd dockerfiles/COPY
docker build -t copy:v1 .
docker run -d -p 8080:80 copy:v1

port:8080
o/p:- Hi, copying from local to image

we can copy from other file to docker file

ADD
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Add also does same as copy but it has 2 extra capabilities
1. it can get files form internet
2. it can extract the files directly into image

create a folder name as ADD in VS code, under ADD create file Dockerfile. add a content as below
FROM almalinux:9
RUN dnf install nginx -y
RUN rm -rf /usr/share/nginx/html/index.html
ADD https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/devops/introduction-to-docker/ /usr/share/nginx/html/index.html
CMD ["nginx", "-g", "daemon off;"]

go to git bash ==> git add . , git commit -m "docker", git push main origin
now the changes reflected in git hub and run git pull in putty it updates the changes.
cd dockerfiles/ADD
docker ps -a
docker ps -a -q  -> shows all containers ID's
docker rm -f `docker ps -a -q`   -> it deletes all containers
docker ps
docker build -t add:v1 .
docker run -d -p 80:80 add:v1
IP:80 o/p:- welcome to nginx -> we didn't get the output of the file
so docker ps -a
docker exec -it containerid bash
cd /usr/share/nginx/html/index.html
chmod +r index.html
IP:80   
o/p: what is docker and all....   in vs code i gave what is docker and all url copied from google and provided.

ENTRYPOINT
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------

create a folder name as ENTRYPOINT in VS code, under ENTRYPOINT create file Dockerfile. add a content as below
FROM almalinux:9
CMD ["ping", "google.com"]

docker build -t entry:v1 .
docker run -d entry:v1   -> this runs ping command continuously will see in logs
docker logs -f containerid   -> ping command runs infinite times
docker rm -f container ID -> removed container now
docker run -d entry:v1 ping yahoo.com => now it is not pinging google.com it is pinging yaahoo.com

deepika@nginx:~/dockerfiles/ENTRYPOINT$ docker run -d entry:v1 ping yahoo.com
c329a57658edfad45dcaa78c63552d6cec05f2f542f0dcb05b171b11a588bfd6
deepika@nginx:~/dockerfiles/ENTRYPOINT$ docker logs -f c329a57658edfad45dcaa78c63552d6cec05f2f542f0dcb05b171b11a588bfd6
PING yahoo.com (74.6.231.20) 56(84) bytes of data.
64 bytes from media-router-fp73.prod.media.vip.ne1.yahoo.com (74.6.231.20): icmp_seq=1 ttl=45 time=49.0 ms
64 bytes from media-router-fp73.prod.media.vip.ne1.yahoo.com (74.6.231.20): icmp_seq=2 ttl=45 time=49.0 ms
CMD can be overridden at runtime.

changed in VS code
FROM almalinux:9
ENTRYPOINT ["ping", "google.com"]
#CMD ["ping", "google.com"]
docker duild -t entry:v1
docker run -d entry:v1
docker logs containerID  -> here it is pinging google IP
docker rm -f containerID
docker run -d entry:v1 ping yahoo.com
docker ps -a
deepika@nginx:~/dockerfiles/ENTRYPOINT$ docker ps -a
CONTAINER ID   IMAGE      COMMAND                  CREATED             STATUS                      PORTS                                 NAMES
98285242caaa   entry:v1   "ping google.com pin…"   37 seconds ago      Exited (2) 37 seconds ago                                         loving_bassi
here see above you cannot override entry point like CMD, if u try to do it will go and append to the entrypoint command.
for better results and best practices CMD can provide ARG to entry point, default args through CMD and ypu can override them at run time.

FROM almalinux:9
CMD ["google.com"]
ENTRYPOINT ["ping"]
docker run -d entry:v1 microsoft.com
o/p:-  this will not ping google.com, this pings microsoft.com

USER
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
For security you should not run containers using root user it must be on normal user atleast last instruction should be some username
create a folder name as USER in VS code, under USER create file Dockerfile. add a content as below
FROM almalinux:9
RUN dnf install nginx -y
CMD ["nginx", "-g", "daemon off;"]

docker build -t user:v1 .
docker run -d -p 8081:80 user:v1
docker exec -it containerID bash
now we have root access, root access is not good y because if any other container can easily connect to container so we are giving user now.
FROM almalinux:9
RUN useradd expense
USER expense
CMD["sleep", "100"]
docker build -t user:v1 .
docker run -d user:v1 
docker exec -it user:v1 bash
now it opens on expense  user

WORKDIR
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
workdir is used to set the current working directory inside docker image.
FROM almalinux:9
RUN mkdir /tmp/docker
RUN cd /tmp/docker
RUN pwd
RUN echo "Hello" > hello.txt
CMD ["sleep", "100"]
docker build -t work:v1 .
docker run -d work:v1
docker exec -it df6d742a92af bash

connected to root
/tmp/docker directories created but it didn't went to cd /tmp/docker and didn't created file here created in root, y because cd will not work here instead of cd we can use WORKDIR.

Below works now, instead of cd using WORKDIR
FROM almalinux:9
RUN mkdir /tmp/docker
WORKDIR /tmp/docker
RUN pwd
RUN echo "Hello" > hello.txt
CMD ["sleep", "100"]

docker build -t work:v1 .
docker run -d work:v1
deepika@nginx:~/dockerfiles/WORKDIR$ docker exec -it 99c751602d5b bash
[root@99c751602d5b docker]# cd /tmp/docker
[root@99c751602d5b docker]# ls
hello.txt
[root@99c751602d5b docker]# cat hello.txt
Hello
[root@99c751602d5b docker]#

ARG
------------------------------------------------------
ARG is used to set the variables at build time only, not inside container

From almalinux:9
ARG course="Devops " \
    Duration="120hrs" 
RUN echo "course: $course, duration: $duration"
CMD ["sleep", "100"]

docker build -t arg:v1 .
docker run -d arg:v1
